WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:06.290
MELISSA: Please welcome
Ken Jennings.

00:00:12.990 --> 00:00:13.170
KEN JENNINGS: Thanks, Melissa.

00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:14.300
Well, thank you all
for coming out.

00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:16.965
It's a pleasure to be here.

00:00:16.965 --> 00:00:19.680
I flew out from Seattle
just to see you guys.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:20.770
It's not a big tech town.

00:00:20.770 --> 00:00:24.180
So it's exciting to be someplace
with a few software

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:25.430
engineers for a change.

00:00:27.970 --> 00:00:28.510
Post-Jeopardy.

00:00:28.510 --> 00:00:30.560
I'm now an author pretty
much full time.

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:32.189
I was a software engineer
before, but

00:00:32.189 --> 00:00:34.150
not a very good one.

00:00:34.150 --> 00:00:36.020
Unlike, I'm sure, anybody who
gets hired at Google.

00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:40.890
So I'm much happier in my second
life as a freelance

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:44.070
writer, where I can work from
home in my pajamas.

00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:50.320
And the book that I have out
today, I guess sort of has

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:55.290
something to do with the
modern information age.

00:00:55.290 --> 00:01:00.140
It's called "Because I Said So!"
The idea is to debunk or

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:04.160
possibly prove all these cliches
that parents are

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:07.620
always harassing their kids
with, don't go swimming until

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:10.910
half an hour after you eat; or
don't pop your knuckles,

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:13.570
you'll get arthritis; or don't
swallow watermelon seeds,

00:01:13.570 --> 00:01:17.260
it'll sprout in your stomach
and you'll die.

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:18.960
We don't all hear all
of these as kids.

00:01:18.960 --> 00:01:21.870
But speaking only for myself, I
know my parents were always

00:01:21.870 --> 00:01:26.160
threatening us with dire things
that would happen if we

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:28.820
did any of these behaviors that
really seemed sort of

00:01:28.820 --> 00:01:29.820
harmless to us.

00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:32.120
And I realize now that I have
kids, that I was starting to

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:32.990
do the same thing.

00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:35.990
I have a 10-year-old boy and a
6-year-old girl and I realize

00:01:35.990 --> 00:01:39.200
that when you're a parent, I
guess I'm now aware of this,

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:40.630
you lie all the time.

00:01:40.630 --> 00:01:40.870
You have to.

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:43.060
You have to lie all the time.

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:45.790
And the lies are
not malicious.

00:01:45.790 --> 00:01:47.230
They're in fact, quite
the opposite.

00:01:47.230 --> 00:01:50.140
You feel like it's a benevolent
lie to tell your

00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:53.040
kids that Santa is going to
bring them presents if they're

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:56.880
good, or that their hamster
actually went to live on

00:01:56.880 --> 00:01:59.910
grandpa's farm, or that
really you love them

00:01:59.910 --> 00:02:01.160
both exactly the same.

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:06.280
I feel like these are pretty
useful lies actually.

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:07.700
There's some utility to this.

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:11.900
But often I would find myself
lying out of more

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:13.080
self-serving reasons.

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:17.150
Just because I felt like
I had to be confident.

00:02:17.150 --> 00:02:18.580
I couldn't show any
sign of weakness.

00:02:18.580 --> 00:02:20.550
Kids are like bears, I guess.

00:02:20.550 --> 00:02:21.750
If your kid asks you, really?

00:02:21.750 --> 00:02:23.480
You to say yes, that's right.

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:24.530
Do what you're told.

00:02:24.530 --> 00:02:25.780
Finish your vegetables.

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:30.260
And more and more often
I realized--

00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:31.590
in fact, I know when
it occurred to me.

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:33.000
This is how the book starts.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.120
My son comes careening into--
we're in my parents' house.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:36.810
My son comes careening around
the corner in the

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:38.950
kitchen with a--

00:02:38.950 --> 00:02:41.080
kids, if there's some place in
the house where they can run

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:42.060
in a circle, they'll do it.

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:42.870
I don't know why.

00:02:42.870 --> 00:02:44.130
He comes running in
with a Tootsie Pop

00:02:44.130 --> 00:02:45.410
sticking out of his mouth.

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:46.930
And I'm like whoa, whoa,
whoa, slow down.

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:48.440
Like what if you fell?

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:51.970
That lollipop could like go
through the back of your soft

00:02:51.970 --> 00:02:52.980
palate in the back of
your mouth and like

00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:54.240
jab you in the brain.

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:56.030
And he was an eight-year-old
boy, so of course he's

00:02:56.030 --> 00:02:56.490
fascinated.

00:02:56.490 --> 00:02:58.320
Like this doesn't scare him.

00:02:58.320 --> 00:02:59.740
This is like, really?

00:02:59.740 --> 00:03:00.360
Is that true?

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:01.680
Could that really happen?

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:03.090
And I realized when he
asked that, I had no

00:03:03.090 --> 00:03:05.410
idea if that was true.

00:03:05.410 --> 00:03:08.070
Like I have done research
on oral trauma?

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:08.530
No.

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:09.690
Like, I have no idea.

00:03:09.690 --> 00:03:13.840
I'm just repeating some thing
that my mom randomly told me

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:17.820
in the late '70s, probably on
the basis of no information as

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:20.840
well, and assuming it's
going to be correct.

00:03:20.840 --> 00:03:22.920
And luckily, we're at
my mom's house.

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:23.500
So I asked her.

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:24.616
I was like, is this true?

00:03:24.616 --> 00:03:26.080
You always used to
tell us that.

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:26.990
And she was like, oh,
I don't know.

00:03:26.990 --> 00:03:30.030
That's just something grandma
used to tell us.

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:31.775
I think it happens in
a Chaim Potok novel.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:37.080
So this is how I'm disappointing
my kids.

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:42.000
Based on my mind vaguely
remembered notions of my mom's

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.580
hazily remembered memory
of a Chaim Potok novel?

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:49.610
Like I understand he's a rabbi
as well as a novelist, but

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:53.270
maybe this is not how I
should be choosing the

00:03:53.270 --> 00:03:54.370
things I tell my kids.

00:03:54.370 --> 00:03:57.150
And I realized these things do
sort of, just sort of turn up

00:03:57.150 --> 00:03:57.970
cyclically.

00:03:57.970 --> 00:04:00.720
Like I'm sure when my son has
kids, now he's going to tell

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.140
them don't run with a Tootsie
Pop in your mouth.

00:04:03.140 --> 00:04:05.520
It'll give your brain
damage if you fall.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:07.400
And again, he will
have no idea.

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:09.620
And I thought, well
maybe there's a--

00:04:09.620 --> 00:04:11.500
I'm sort of a full-time
trivia author now.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.710
Somehow I'm in this weird niche,
thanks to Alex Trebek.

00:04:13.710 --> 00:04:16.500
Like maybe there's
a book in this.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:20.940
So I started gathering these
myths, gathering from memory

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:21.800
my own childhood.

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:23.190
What did my parents tell me?

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:24.580
Don't eat the cookie dough.

00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:26.690
You'll get worms.

00:04:26.690 --> 00:04:27.580
Don't run outside.

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:28.190
You'll get worms.

00:04:28.190 --> 00:04:30.190
I guess worms were very
big in the late '70s.

00:04:30.190 --> 00:04:32.840
Like no matter what it
was, we'd get worms.

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:35.420
And every time I saw a friend,
I'd ask them, hey, what were

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:37.330
these cliches that your
parents were always

00:04:37.330 --> 00:04:38.300
threatening you with?

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:40.640
I want to see if these things
are actually true.

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:44.580
And one person would remember
their mom said that you lose

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:46.440
10% of your body heat
through your head.

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:50.430
Or somebody else would remember
their dad saying that

00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:53.100
if you swallow gum, it'll sit in
your stomach undigested for

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:54.960
seven years.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:56.440
And he was fascinated by that.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:57.700
And so I started there.

00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:00.160
I started to collect a little
spreadsheet of these things.

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:03.350
And I was getting close
to having enough for a

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:04.190
book, and not quite.

00:05:04.190 --> 00:05:06.960
So I did what I'm sure any of
you would do and I had Reddit

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:11.490
crowd-source the rest
of this for me.

00:05:11.490 --> 00:05:13.100
Hey Reddit, what are some
of the weird things your

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:14.270
parents told you?

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:16.020
P.S., write my book for me.

00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:22.430
And in with all the goofy bacon
jokes and screeds about

00:05:22.430 --> 00:05:26.290
marijuana legalization, a lot
of people suggested great

00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:28.370
parental cliches that I had
not thought of, that were

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:30.220
really, really good
fits for the book.

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:34.100
And I started to research
these things.

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:37.010
And it turned out that
surprisingly, maybe I'm

00:05:37.010 --> 00:05:38.830
jumping the gun a little here,
but surprisingly there's

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:40.180
actually a lot of
good scientific

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:41.430
research on some of these.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:45.680
I guess enough kids were told
that there's a five-second

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:48.080
rule between when you drop food
and when you can pick it

00:05:48.080 --> 00:05:52.070
up in the shopping mall food
court, enough kids are told

00:05:52.070 --> 00:05:53.191
this, that many of them
have gone to college.

00:05:53.191 --> 00:05:56.150
And there are now four or five
good academic studies on

00:05:56.150 --> 00:06:00.820
whether or not the five-second
rule exists.

00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:02.940
Spoilers, it doesn't.

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:05.090
Food gets contaminated when
it lands on something.

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:09.510
So if you drop it and there
is rat poison or bleach or

00:06:09.510 --> 00:06:13.370
salmonella or something on the
floor, it's contaminated then.

00:06:13.370 --> 00:06:15.390
You don't get some magical
window where the microbes

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:20.380
wait, three, four, five, go.

00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:22.960
But by the same token, they
can only get these results

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:26.150
when they pretreat the floor
with salmonella.

00:06:26.150 --> 00:06:29.220
When they do that, the food
comes back contaminated.

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:31.860
Every time they run these
experiments on regular dorm

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:35.780
cafeteria floors, it's
perfectly fine.

00:06:35.780 --> 00:06:37.960
And in many cases, a surprising
number of these

00:06:37.960 --> 00:06:40.560
were coming back false, which
is what I wanted.

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:44.500
The book is no good if all
these things are true.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:46.300
And by the same token, there
were some selection bias.

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:49.650
Obviously if something turns out
to be surprisingly false,

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:50.660
in the book it goes.

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:54.020
I found out that that thing your
parents told you about

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:58.160
having to drink eight glasses
of water a day, it's bogus.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:06:59.410
It's actually dangerous.

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:02.430
It's possible to over hydrate
your brain and people have

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:03.280
died from this.

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:06.160
Whereas, the body's thirst
mechanism actually kicks in

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:07.950
long before dehydration.

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:09.710
So you're actually good just
drinking water when you're

00:07:09.710 --> 00:07:12.890
thirsty and not trying to get to
some number that was forced

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:16.530
on you by a seventh grade
home ec teacher.

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:17.510
But there was some
selection bias.

00:07:17.510 --> 00:07:18.960
Obviously, I would pick
the ones that were

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:21.400
interesting to debunk.

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:24.067
If it turns out that it really
is good advice to not play in

00:07:24.067 --> 00:07:26.630
the street, that was
a less interesting

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:27.600
section in the book.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:31.400
Here's sort of one sample entry
that I'll read, which I

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:33.220
already mentioned, about
swallowed gum sitting in your

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:36.010
stomach undigested
for seven years.

00:07:36.010 --> 00:07:39.170
It's just a threat if you
swallow your gum.

00:07:39.170 --> 00:07:41.070
Did you guys hear this as
kids or is just me?

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:44.620
My parents were firm
believers in this.

00:07:44.620 --> 00:07:46.820
So from the book, could
this really be true?

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:50.600
If I swallow a piece of gum
today, will it really emerge

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:53.320
Rip van Winkle-like into some
futuristic Japanese-style

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:55.380
toilet in the year 2020?

00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:58.040
Is there a possibility that
tonight I will poop the piece

00:07:58.040 --> 00:07:59.930
of gum that I accidentally
swallowed during "Big Momma's

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:03.570
House 2?"

00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:05.980
When pondering these questions
with my friend Raj, he

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:08.540
remembered that as a child, he
wondered what would happen if

00:08:08.540 --> 00:08:10.620
he swallowed two
pieces of gum?

00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:13.110
Would they be trapped for
seven years or 14?

00:08:13.110 --> 00:08:15.140
In other words, would they
serve their sentences

00:08:15.140 --> 00:08:17.710
consecutively or concurrently?

00:08:17.710 --> 00:08:20.300
I hate to pop your bubble, but
the answer is neither.

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:23.310
Swallowed gum routinely gets
furloughed within 24 hours,

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:25.190
like a diplomat or a Kennedy.

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:27.970
It's true that about a quarter
of chewing gum is the gum base

00:08:27.970 --> 00:08:31.120
itself, a completely food-free
substance made up of latexes,

00:08:31.120 --> 00:08:33.450
resins, waxes, and
emulsifiers.

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:35.635
Your gastrointestinal tract
could work on that for seven

00:08:35.635 --> 00:08:37.559
years and have no luck
digesting it.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.570
But that's not what happens.

00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:41.669
Quote "That would mean that
every single person who ever

00:08:41.669 --> 00:08:43.409
swallowed gum within the last
seven years would have

00:08:43.409 --> 00:08:45.960
evidence of the gum in their
digestive tract," Dr. David

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:49.020
Milov told "Scientific
American." "On occasion, we'll

00:08:49.020 --> 00:08:51.200
see a piece of swallowed
gum in a colonoscopy.

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:53.140
But usually, it's not something
that's any more than

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:56.080
a week old." Your intestine
eliminates gum the same way it

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:58.560
eliminates half-chewed corn
kernels and anything else

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:00.520
that's too tough to digest,
out the rectum

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:01.500
within a day or two.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:02.830
I guess I didn't realize people
were going to be eating

00:09:02.830 --> 00:09:06.270
lunch during this.

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:08.680
I apologize in advance,
especially for the thing

00:09:08.680 --> 00:09:11.690
that's about to happen
in two paragraphs.

00:09:11.690 --> 00:09:15.590
If you're almost there, you
may want to finish up.

00:09:15.590 --> 00:09:17.960
However, Dr. Milov also led the
team that published the

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:20.600
landmark study, "Chewing
Gum Bezoars of the

00:09:20.600 --> 00:09:23.520
Gastrointestinal Tract," in a
1998 issue of the medical

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:26.290
journal "Pediatrics." A
"bezoar": is a clump of

00:09:26.290 --> 00:09:27.930
undigested stuff that
gets trapped in

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:30.050
the stomach or intestine.

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:32.200
The wonderful name comes from
the Persian word for antidote,

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.420
since animal bezoars, sort of
like those owl pellets you had

00:09:35.420 --> 00:09:37.570
to dissect in eighth grade, were
anciently thought to have

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:39.010
remarkable health properties.

00:09:39.010 --> 00:09:42.060
Most bezoars are boluses
of food or pills.

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:44.380
Sometimes in rare cases
of Rapunzel syndrome,

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:45.330
they're made of--

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:46.040
anyone?

00:09:46.040 --> 00:09:46.450
AUDIENCE: Hair.

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:48.350
KEN JENNINGS: Swallowed
hair, ugh.

00:09:48.350 --> 00:09:50.690
And sometimes, very rarely,
they can be

00:09:50.690 --> 00:09:51.670
made of chewing gum.

00:09:51.670 --> 00:09:55.200
Dr. Milov's team found three
cases of young children whose,

00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:57.690
this is a quote from the report,
"means of discarding

00:09:57.690 --> 00:10:00.260
their gum (swallowing) was well
known to the families and

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:03.480
was a source of levity." Well,
nobody was laughing when the

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:06.190
gum swallowing led to chronic
constipation and, finally,

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:08.930
surgery when laxatives
proved powerless.

00:10:08.930 --> 00:10:10.900
If you want your kids to quit
swallowing their gum, here's

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:12.150
the money quote.

00:10:12.150 --> 00:10:14.645
"This clean-out regimen produced
no results after four

00:10:14.645 --> 00:10:16.680
days." In other words,
the laxatives.

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:19.120
"On the fifth day, the child
was brought in for manual

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:22.330
disimpaction under conscious
sedation and rectal suction

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:28.560
biopsy." On removal of the--
here's the money quote, "On

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:31.930
removal of the leading edge of
the fecoma, a taffy-like trail

00:10:31.930 --> 00:10:33.910
of fecal material remained
in the rectum.

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:36.040
The mass was eventually manually
withdrawn and was

00:10:36.040 --> 00:10:38.940
primarily made up
of chewing gum."

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:41.760
Wow, I hope these parents kept
the rectal suction biopsy

00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:44.230
video on hand to show
future prom dates.

00:10:44.230 --> 00:10:46.790
But keep in mind, this was a kid
who was swallowing five to

00:10:46.790 --> 00:10:49.240
seven pieces of gum per day.

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:51.800
Other cases only got serious
when stuff like coins got

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:54.060
swallowed and trapping in the
Wrigley's brand butt plug.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:56.710
So don't worry, the occasional
accidentally swallowed piece

00:10:56.710 --> 00:10:57.780
of gum isn't going
to do any harm.

00:10:57.780 --> 00:11:00.150
You'd have to be the Hunter S.
Thompson of gum swallowing to

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:01.810
get into medical trouble.

00:11:01.810 --> 00:11:03.780
But prepare to be embarrassed,
if you're caught.

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:06.570
Dr. Milov writes that, quote,
"The rainbow of fused

00:11:06.570 --> 00:11:09.750
multicolored gum fragments in
the removed fecoma is easily

00:11:09.750 --> 00:11:13.090
recognized by physician and
family as old gum." In the

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:15.640
end, maybe I'm just weird that
that actually sounds sort of

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:18.250
beautiful, other than the part
where it gets pulled out of

00:11:18.250 --> 00:11:19.480
somebody's butt.

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:21.350
And then the verdict is false.

00:11:21.350 --> 00:11:23.840
All the myths and the cliches
in the book are given a

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:25.600
verdict on the scale
of true to false.

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:27.880
And many of them do fall
somewhere in the middle.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:32.160
Some of them are true with a
nyeh, false with a-- but.

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:34.370
On some of them, the research
is ongoing.

00:11:34.370 --> 00:11:37.020
For many years, for example,
researchers were pretty sure

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:41.000
that cold weather did nothing
to make people

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:42.680
susceptible to colds.

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:44.450
They knew that there
was a cold season.

00:11:44.450 --> 00:11:46.360
But there's still not widespread
agreement on what

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:46.780
causes that.

00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:49.320
Is it just people packed indoors
together during the

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:50.650
winter, sharing germs?

00:11:50.650 --> 00:11:52.830
Is it because school
is in session?

00:11:52.830 --> 00:11:55.020
Is it because the cold
lowers your immunity?

00:11:55.020 --> 00:11:59.120
Is it because the virus does
better in cold conditions?

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:00.230
Nobody is 100% sure.

00:12:00.230 --> 00:12:01.500
They were pretty sure it
wasn't temperature.

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:04.360
Because they would dab infected
mucus on people--

00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:06.890
again, sorry if you're eating--
on people's noses, at

00:12:06.890 --> 00:12:07.680
different temperatures.

00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:09.830
And they would find no
relationship between who got a

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:11.870
cold and who was cold.

00:12:11.870 --> 00:12:15.520
But there's some new research
out of a university in Wales,

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:19.670
where they tried to model how
people catch colds in a more

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:21.780
organic way.

00:12:21.780 --> 00:12:24.350
During cold season, they would
have people sit in a lab, with

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:29.040
their feet in buckets of cold
water, and then compare who

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:32.050
caught a cold, just in the next
month of running around

00:12:32.050 --> 00:12:34.310
Wales, to the control group
that was not sitting with

00:12:34.310 --> 00:12:35.300
their feet in cold water.

00:12:35.300 --> 00:12:36.780
And they found a pretty
strong causal link.

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:40.655
Something about having cold
feet actually made these

00:12:40.655 --> 00:12:41.260
people catch colds.

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:44.150
So as crazy as it sounds,
your mom was right.

00:12:44.150 --> 00:12:46.900
These people might be catching
cold because they didn't put

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:49.790
on galoshes, or because they
went outside with wet hair, or

00:12:49.790 --> 00:12:52.290
all the things your mom
was freaked about.

00:12:52.290 --> 00:12:56.330
So I think there is some comfort
here for parents who--

00:12:56.330 --> 00:12:58.180
there is some vindication for
parents who have been saying

00:12:58.180 --> 00:12:59.700
that breakfast is the
most important meal

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:00.400
of the day or whatever.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:02.480
Some of these things are true.

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:04.110
But the vast majority are not.

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:05.920
And that's trouble
in our house.

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:09.830
My son read a galley, an
early copy of the book.

00:13:09.830 --> 00:13:13.570
And now he is way
over-informed.

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:16.110
It's gotten to the point where
my wife will be like, Dylan,

00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:17.100
you're sitting to
close to the TV.

00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:18.110
Get back on the couch.

00:13:18.110 --> 00:13:18.930
And he won't even look up.

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:20.050
He'll be like, no I'm not.

00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:22.840
Dad says it's fine.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:24.100
It's just temporary
eye strain.

00:13:29.250 --> 00:13:30.805
I think this is hilarious.

00:13:30.805 --> 00:13:34.720
If my wife were here, I don't
think she's such a fan.

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:37.510
And you realize what
the utility is to a

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:38.460
lot of these myths.

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:41.160
Not only does it make the
parent look wise and

00:13:41.160 --> 00:13:47.300
authoritative, oftentimes I am
sure these things arise out of

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:48.740
the need to--

00:13:48.740 --> 00:13:51.260
you want to shut down some
annoying behavior.

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:53.330
You don't want your kids
popping their knuckles,

00:13:53.330 --> 00:13:56.130
because if you hear that sound
one more time, you're going to

00:13:56.130 --> 00:13:58.710
go crash the car or something.

00:13:58.710 --> 00:14:00.315
And so you tell your kid
that causes arthritis.

00:14:00.315 --> 00:14:01.565
And it's not really true.

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:06.170
But kids fall for
a lot of this.

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:09.600
And I'm sort of concerned that
one effect of this might be

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:16.450
that as these parental paranoias
sort of accumulate

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:19.440
over generations, that we sort
of forget how they started.

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:23.720
That they started as
well-intended ways of

00:14:23.720 --> 00:14:24.420
protecting your kids.

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:26.880
And we start to think there is
some terrible threat if your

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:31.320
child swallows a watermelon
seed, or picks up a dirty

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:36.990
feather at the playground, or
looks at the microwave while

00:14:36.990 --> 00:14:39.670
it's running, or whatever
these things are.

00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:40.950
Writes on his skin with
a ballpoint pen.

00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:43.380
I had a seventh grade biology
teacher freak out because I

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:45.770
was drawing something on my hand
with a pen and that was

00:14:45.770 --> 00:14:47.050
going to cause cancer
or something.

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:52.490
And over time, you get this
gradual accumulation of these

00:14:52.490 --> 00:14:53.560
parental paranoias.

00:14:53.560 --> 00:14:57.370
And the result is our kids start
getting more and more

00:14:57.370 --> 00:14:59.840
cushioned, more and more
bubble-wrapped for any kind of

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:01.710
experimentation or fun.

00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:05.560
And before long, you get the
kind of helicopter parents you

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:08.780
read about in scary "Time"
magazine cover packages of

00:15:08.780 --> 00:15:10.780
these parents who never let
their kids do any of the

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:11.300
things that--

00:15:11.300 --> 00:15:13.030
I got to ride my bike
to school as a kid.

00:15:13.030 --> 00:15:14.160
But no, you can't
do that today.

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:17.550
Kids who can't climb trees.

00:15:17.550 --> 00:15:19.280
You see crazy examples.

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:22.110
I read a "Dear Abby" column,
where she told parents to take

00:15:22.110 --> 00:15:25.400
a picture of their kids every
day leaving the house in that

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:28.360
day's clothes, because that
way if they got kidnapped,

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:31.680
she's got something to
show to the cops.

00:15:31.680 --> 00:15:34.800
This is like a serious
well-intended solution.

00:15:34.800 --> 00:15:36.050
Or--

00:15:37.810 --> 00:15:38.540
this is great.

00:15:38.540 --> 00:15:41.810
I've actually heard about
universities that now have

00:15:41.810 --> 00:15:45.050
sort of mommy cams in the dorms
so that your mom can

00:15:45.050 --> 00:15:47.580
like keep an eye on what's
going on in the

00:15:47.580 --> 00:15:49.950
old residence hall.

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:52.960
Companies are preparing parent
packets, like big accounting

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:56.490
companies are now preparing
parent packets for their new

00:15:56.490 --> 00:15:59.010
job interviews every year
because often a concerned mom

00:15:59.010 --> 00:16:01.810
or dad will come along.

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:03.480
And so I'm sort of worried
that in our well-intended

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:06.230
desire to keep our kids safe,
we're actually making kids

00:16:06.230 --> 00:16:09.390
unhappy, unable to cope with the
modern world, unconfident

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:10.400
about the modern world.

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:12.760
The perfect example is like
don't talk to strangers.

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:15.830
What could be a less
controversial piece of advice?

00:16:15.830 --> 00:16:17.680
And of course, your kids
shouldn't talk to strangers.

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:19.920
Actually if you talk to child
safety advocacy groups now,

00:16:19.920 --> 00:16:21.580
they say that's like the worst
thing you could say.

00:16:21.580 --> 00:16:24.150
Never tell your kid not
to talk to strangers.

00:16:24.150 --> 00:16:25.140
Kids don't understand that.

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:27.110
It just makes them insecure
about adults.

00:16:27.110 --> 00:16:30.200
There have been cases where a
kid got lost and then tried to

00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:33.060
hide from all the people that
were looking for him because

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:35.820
they were strangers.

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:38.130
And instead, they say what
you need to do is

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:39.230
teach kids to be confident.

00:16:39.230 --> 00:16:41.150
If they get in that kind of
situation, they need to know

00:16:41.150 --> 00:16:44.930
which adults they should
be looking to for help.

00:16:44.930 --> 00:16:46.450
Go to somebody in uniform.

00:16:46.450 --> 00:16:47.900
Go to somebody who works
for the store.

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:49.950
Try to find another
mom with kids.

00:16:49.950 --> 00:16:51.770
There's actually good, practical
advice you can give

00:16:51.770 --> 00:16:54.160
kids that doesn't scare them.

00:16:54.160 --> 00:16:56.870
And instead, we've created
this whole industry based

00:16:56.870 --> 00:16:58.060
around stranger danger.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:00.680
This idea that some creepy guy
in a white van is going to

00:17:00.680 --> 00:17:03.570
grab your kid, when really the
idea of a stranger kidnapping

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:06.810
a kid is something that only
happens like on the order of a

00:17:06.810 --> 00:17:09.770
few dozen times every year
in this country.

00:17:09.770 --> 00:17:13.369
Most of the, a child vanishes
every n minutes, stats you

00:17:13.369 --> 00:17:16.619
hear, it's all people the
family know, it's a

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:18.030
noncustodial parent
or something.

00:17:18.030 --> 00:17:19.319
But it's how we create
the method

00:17:19.319 --> 00:17:20.819
of this random kidnapper.

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:26.650
So hopefully, actually debunking
some of these things

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:29.080
will let parents breathe a
little easier and let their

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:30.360
kids be kids.

00:17:30.360 --> 00:17:32.220
The cool thing about writing
this book today is it's

00:17:32.220 --> 00:17:34.260
actually possible to
be written today.

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:36.690
We live in an age where
information is much more

00:17:36.690 --> 00:17:39.080
available to the lay
person, public

00:17:39.080 --> 00:17:40.730
interest writer like me.

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:45.210
If I don't know whether or not
apple seeds are poisonous, I

00:17:45.210 --> 00:17:46.460
can Bing it.

00:17:48.670 --> 00:17:50.030
I'm just kidding.

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:52.980
I would google it.

00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:55.940
When I was a kid, I was sort of
a trivia nerd kid you'll be

00:17:55.940 --> 00:17:59.510
shocked to hear, when I was
10 or 11 years old.

00:17:59.510 --> 00:18:00.770
We did not have Google.

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:06.750
We lived in this strange
internet-free world where the

00:18:06.750 --> 00:18:10.850
real scoop on myths like this,
if they got delivered at all,

00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:14.530
came in the forms of often out
of print paperbacks that you'd

00:18:14.530 --> 00:18:16.490
have to find in a
used bookstore.

00:18:16.490 --> 00:18:18.540
And I remember knowing, to this
day I know which of these

00:18:18.540 --> 00:18:19.480
books held which things.

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:22.060
I know that back before the
internet, if you wanted to

00:18:22.060 --> 00:18:25.490
know a best guess as to what the
secret herbs and spices in

00:18:25.490 --> 00:18:28.130
the Colonel's chicken was,
that's in a book called "Big

00:18:28.130 --> 00:18:30.180
Secrets" by William
Poundstone.

00:18:30.180 --> 00:18:35.140
And if you want to know the
scoop about the fact that in

00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:37.520
Columbus's day, nobody really
thought the world was flat,

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:38.390
contrary to popular belief.

00:18:38.390 --> 00:18:40.270
That was in Tom Burnam's book,
"The Dictionary of

00:18:40.270 --> 00:18:41.010
Misinformation."

00:18:41.010 --> 00:18:42.790
There were all these sort of
pop reference books where

00:18:42.790 --> 00:18:43.945
people knew this stuff.

00:18:43.945 --> 00:18:45.940
Of course today, we
don't need that.

00:18:45.940 --> 00:18:47.720
All this kind of stuff
is well handled

00:18:47.720 --> 00:18:49.780
by Snopes, by Wikipedia.

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:51.880
It's well-indexed by Google.

00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:55.350
All this stuff should just
be a click away.

00:18:55.350 --> 00:19:00.030
And the experience of fighting
and getting my ass kicked by

00:19:00.030 --> 00:19:03.390
Watson sort of made me think
what are the implications of

00:19:03.390 --> 00:19:07.410
living in this world where
our search engines or our

00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:11.480
smartphones can do lots of our
stuff remembering stuff for

00:19:11.480 --> 00:19:13.080
us, a lot of our stuff
remembering for us?

00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:17.970
I realized after losing
to Google--

00:19:17.970 --> 00:19:21.680
or to Google, Freudian slip,
after losing to Watson, I'm

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:28.070
someone who always drew a lot
of I guess self-esteem from

00:19:28.070 --> 00:19:30.660
being the guy who's good
at remembering stuff.

00:19:30.660 --> 00:19:34.040
It used to be a valuable thing
in the workplace to know who's

00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:35.750
the person in the office you go
to when you can't remember

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:37.630
the name of the bassist
of in that band?

00:19:37.630 --> 00:19:39.530
Or what's the name of
that character actor

00:19:39.530 --> 00:19:40.450
on that one TV show?

00:19:40.450 --> 00:19:43.590
And I was always that guy, at
school, or in the dorms, or in

00:19:43.590 --> 00:19:45.210
the office.

00:19:45.210 --> 00:19:46.440
And today, nobody
needs that guy.

00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:49.340
That guy is out of work.

00:19:49.340 --> 00:19:51.420
If you don't remember the name
of some guy, you look it up on

00:19:51.420 --> 00:19:51.860
your phone.

00:19:51.860 --> 00:19:53.110
And it's super easy.

00:19:55.770 --> 00:20:02.220
And in effect, when I lost to
Watson, I sort of felt like

00:20:02.220 --> 00:20:04.920
the first person in America
who'd lost his job to this new

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:09.400
generation of thinking machine,
just like a 1970s

00:20:09.400 --> 00:20:13.640
Detroit factory worker getting
pushed off the assembly line

00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:17.870
by the robot that can do his
job much faster and more

00:20:17.870 --> 00:20:18.740
reliably than him.

00:20:18.740 --> 00:20:22.260
And I felt like I was the first
one of those guys for

00:20:22.260 --> 00:20:26.110
the information age, which
was a great honor.

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:28.230
And the more I read up on this,
I feel like I'm not

00:20:28.230 --> 00:20:29.210
going to be the last one.

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:34.850
There's lots of other
sort of--

00:20:34.850 --> 00:20:36.840
I don't want say menial, but
sort of low-level information

00:20:36.840 --> 00:20:41.600
gathering jobs where Watson or
technologies like it are

00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:44.310
becoming very good.

00:20:44.310 --> 00:20:46.500
I'm sure there are probably
people in this room working on

00:20:46.500 --> 00:20:48.060
these technologies.

00:20:48.060 --> 00:20:51.230
Pharmacists, almost all that
job can be automated.

00:20:51.230 --> 00:20:54.040
In fact, lots of medical kinds
of lab work and diagnosis is

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:56.240
now getting to the point where
it can be automated.

00:20:56.240 --> 00:20:58.070
IBM has been very clear
that Watson is going

00:20:58.070 --> 00:20:58.670
into health care now.

00:20:58.670 --> 00:21:01.230
I assume that's less
controversial than Homeland

00:21:01.230 --> 00:21:02.910
Security or something.

00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:06.600
Really, our mass information
collecting and processing

00:21:06.600 --> 00:21:08.910
software, it's just going
to cure cancer.

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:12.740
Don't worry about government
contracts at all.

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:17.960
And paralegals, for example.

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:20.290
There's lots of jobs where
people doing low-level

00:21:20.290 --> 00:21:23.420
information collection that
really a pretty short Shell

00:21:23.420 --> 00:21:26.230
script could probably do
your job now, sir.

00:21:26.230 --> 00:21:27.050
And what does that
mean for us?

00:21:27.050 --> 00:21:29.740
What does that mean in a world
where we don't have to know

00:21:29.740 --> 00:21:31.160
stuff anymore?

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:33.740
What's going to happen
our brains?

00:21:33.740 --> 00:21:36.210
The book I wrote before this was
called "Maphead." It was

00:21:36.210 --> 00:21:38.110
about my love of maps
and geography.

00:21:38.110 --> 00:21:40.410
There's a chapter on--

00:21:40.410 --> 00:21:41.510
anybody here from Google Geo?

00:21:41.510 --> 00:21:43.420
There's like a whole chapter
on Google, ayeh.

00:21:43.420 --> 00:21:45.530
There's a whole chapter on
the new digital mapping

00:21:45.530 --> 00:21:47.690
technologies and what
that means for us.

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:52.400
And I talked to quite a few
researchers in the book, who

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:57.310
sort of felt like the new maps
have the potential to be a new

00:21:57.310 --> 00:21:58.630
golden age for mapping.

00:21:58.630 --> 00:22:01.820
There's also the downside of
what GPS is doing to us.

00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:04.200
If we outsource the part of our
brain that navigates and

00:22:04.200 --> 00:22:06.920
does sense of direction to a
little talking voice on our

00:22:06.920 --> 00:22:09.200
dashboard, this is the reason
why you always read in the

00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:11.290
paper about people driving into
lakes and driving onto

00:22:11.290 --> 00:22:12.130
railroad tracks.

00:22:12.130 --> 00:22:14.070
They just obey the little
talking voice.

00:22:14.070 --> 00:22:17.650
How I was supposed to know
that was a lake?

00:22:17.650 --> 00:22:19.750
It's like how we all used
to be able to--

00:22:19.750 --> 00:22:21.660
15 years ago, we were all really
good at memorizing

00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:22.960
seven digit numbers.

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:25.800
And now like, I don't even know
my phone number because

00:22:25.800 --> 00:22:27.190
there's no use for it anymore.

00:22:27.190 --> 00:22:29.630
So what if our phones and our
search engines can do

00:22:29.630 --> 00:22:31.930
all this for us?

00:22:31.930 --> 00:22:36.710
I hope that our ability to
remember facts doesn't atrophy

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:39.170
in the same way that our ability
to remember phone

00:22:39.170 --> 00:22:43.470
numbers and our ability to not
drive into lakes has sort of

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:45.100
changed in the past few years.

00:22:45.100 --> 00:22:49.020
I believe there is still some
utility to knowing a fact off

00:22:49.020 --> 00:22:50.270
the top of your head.

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:55.420
We were actually talking
about this earlier.

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:58.880
It's great that when there's
something on the tip of our

00:22:58.880 --> 00:23:02.550
tongue that we don't know, thank
goodness we can google.

00:23:02.550 --> 00:23:04.220
And it's not just
idle curiosity.

00:23:04.220 --> 00:23:09.400
Often that Google search might
be for something more urgent.

00:23:09.400 --> 00:23:12.310
But imagine what it means to
us that we know facts.

00:23:12.310 --> 00:23:13.400
What does that do for us?

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:15.800
In education, I guess now
there's sort of an emphasis on

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:17.960
knowing how to think rather than
knowing what to think.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:21.680
There's less of an emphasis on
making sure that kids are

00:23:21.680 --> 00:23:24.640
chock-full of dates and
so forth, dates and

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:25.490
formulas, and what not.

00:23:25.490 --> 00:23:28.160
Because ahh, they can
look that up.

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:31.310
I think there is still virtue
in knowing facts.

00:23:31.310 --> 00:23:33.120
If there are two advantages to
knowing something off the top

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:37.540
your head versus having to whip
out your phone or on your

00:23:37.540 --> 00:23:39.800
console, I would say it's
probably the advantage of

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:41.860
scale and the advantage
of time.

00:23:41.860 --> 00:23:44.020
The first is an advantage
of volume.

00:23:44.020 --> 00:23:46.600
The fact that we live in a
information age means that

00:23:46.600 --> 00:23:47.790
it's easier to get a hold
of information.

00:23:47.790 --> 00:23:50.210
It also means there's
exponentially more information

00:23:50.210 --> 00:23:52.940
coming at us at all times.

00:23:52.940 --> 00:23:55.500
Sure, there have been great
Renaissance men in history,

00:23:55.500 --> 00:23:58.430
Thomas Jefferson, and Ben
Franklin, Leonardo da Vinci.

00:23:58.430 --> 00:24:02.740
But notice how they lived sort
of close to the Renaissance.

00:24:02.740 --> 00:24:04.200
There was a lot less
to know back then.

00:24:04.200 --> 00:24:06.900
You put Jefferson on "Jeopardy"
today, and he's

00:24:06.900 --> 00:24:10.210
really going to be struggling
at nuclear physics or '70s

00:24:10.210 --> 00:24:12.210
sit-coms, or hip-hop.

00:24:12.210 --> 00:24:13.810
I mean he's going to get
his butt kicked.

00:24:13.810 --> 00:24:16.580
There's just more to know more,
more to know today than

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:20.000
there was for the guy in the
16th century or the 18th

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:21.970
century, who could
know everything.

00:24:21.970 --> 00:24:23.220
And it's global.

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:28.250
My vacation plans could get
affected by a volcano in

00:24:28.250 --> 00:24:34.200
Iceland, or on the darker side,
a terrorist cell in

00:24:34.200 --> 00:24:37.430
Pakistan, or the
Greek economy.

00:24:37.430 --> 00:24:39.640
Little things happening a world
away, can really affect

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:42.770
my day-to-day life, in a world
that wasn't true in Leonardo's

00:24:42.770 --> 00:24:45.340
time or in Jefferson's time.

00:24:45.340 --> 00:24:47.960
And to make good decisions based
on all these facts, we

00:24:47.960 --> 00:24:48.790
need to synthesize them.

00:24:48.790 --> 00:24:52.030
And that only happens when we
have these facts, I believe,

00:24:52.030 --> 00:24:53.900
at our fingertips.

00:24:53.900 --> 00:24:55.030
Let's say I'm trying
to decide--

00:24:55.030 --> 00:24:55.850
we'll go back in time a month.

00:24:55.850 --> 00:24:57.100
I'll trying to decide
who to vote for.

00:25:00.080 --> 00:25:02.060
I learned already, my map work,
that less than a quarter

00:25:02.060 --> 00:25:05.120
of Americans can find Iraq
and Afghanistan on a map.

00:25:05.120 --> 00:25:07.720
It's closer to 10%.

00:25:07.720 --> 00:25:10.310
Ladies and gentlemen, this
is who's voting on

00:25:10.310 --> 00:25:12.770
your foreign policy.

00:25:12.770 --> 00:25:16.480
And it strikes me that for me
to even make a well-informed

00:25:16.480 --> 00:25:19.680
decision as a citizen on which
candidate I'm going to vote

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:21.670
for in that arena, I should
know more than that.

00:25:21.670 --> 00:25:24.580
Not only should I know the
relative locations of Iraq and

00:25:24.580 --> 00:25:27.090
Afghanistan, I should have some
idea of what I think the

00:25:27.090 --> 00:25:29.030
conditions are there, what I
think the right plan is going

00:25:29.030 --> 00:25:30.570
forward, and so forth.

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:33.260
And that's true not just for
foreign policy, but for dozens

00:25:33.260 --> 00:25:34.830
of other arenas as well.

00:25:34.830 --> 00:25:37.000
And if I am literally going to
sit there and have to goggle

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:38.640
every one of those questions
before I vote,

00:25:38.640 --> 00:25:39.500
we know what happens.

00:25:39.500 --> 00:25:41.490
People don't sit there and
google thousands of questions

00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:43.180
before they fill out
their ballot.

00:25:43.180 --> 00:25:45.390
They just end up doing a really
half-assed job, based

00:25:45.390 --> 00:25:48.260
on really poor knowledge.

00:25:48.260 --> 00:25:53.280
Whereas I believe if more of
those facts were literally in

00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:56.290
their heads, those would be
the building block to more

00:25:56.290 --> 00:25:57.880
informed decisions
on a daily basis.

00:25:57.880 --> 00:26:00.950
Not just voting, but better
informed decisions about where

00:26:00.950 --> 00:26:03.320
to go to eat, or what's quickest
way to drive from

00:26:03.320 --> 00:26:06.780
here to there, or what should
my major be, should I

00:26:06.780 --> 00:26:10.260
interview here or there?

00:26:10.260 --> 00:26:12.660
The decisions we make fairly
regularly, but can have a big

00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:13.600
effect on our lives.

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:16.920
The other advantage I would say
to knowing stuff in our

00:26:16.920 --> 00:26:20.270
heads versus on our phones would
be an advantage of time.

00:26:20.270 --> 00:26:23.775
The story I always think of here
is a little British girl.

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:27.620
She's about 10 years old.

00:26:27.620 --> 00:26:28.640
So that would be the
fourth grade.

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:29.920
Do they have that there?

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:32.740
Well, what would be a fourth
grader in our system, on

00:26:32.740 --> 00:26:35.710
vacation with her parents,
in Thailand.

00:26:35.710 --> 00:26:39.160
She is at the beach one
day with her parents.

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:42.920
And she comes running up in the
morning and says, mom and

00:26:42.920 --> 00:26:44.820
dad, I think we should
get off the beach.

00:26:44.820 --> 00:26:45.510
And I'm like, what
do you mean?

00:26:45.510 --> 00:26:46.550
We just got here.

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:49.970
And she said well,
look out to sea.

00:26:49.970 --> 00:26:53.820
The level of the tide has
gone down quite a bit.

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:55.970
The tide's gone way out
since we've been here.

00:26:55.970 --> 00:26:58.860
And now there's starting to be
like big, churning waves and

00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:01.280
bubbles further out to sea.

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:02.790
And their parents are like,
what does that mean?

00:27:02.790 --> 00:27:04.940
And she said well, we just
learned two weeks ago and Mr.

00:27:04.940 --> 00:27:07.060
Kurney's geography class,
this is the

00:27:07.060 --> 00:27:08.170
first sign of a tsunami.

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:11.460
This is what you see before
the wave hits.

00:27:11.460 --> 00:27:13.760
And their parents are
like, are you sure?

00:27:13.760 --> 00:27:14.910
Like are you saying there's
going to be a tsunami?

00:27:14.910 --> 00:27:15.920
And she's like, that's
what we learned.

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:18.380
And somehow this little girl
convinces her parents that

00:27:18.380 --> 00:27:20.820
this really is a early warning
sign of a tsunami.

00:27:20.820 --> 00:27:21.530
So they get off the beach.

00:27:21.530 --> 00:27:22.385
They tell the life guard.

00:27:22.385 --> 00:27:24.390
The life guard clears
the beach.

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:28.156
And within less than an hour,
sure enough, the beach is

00:27:28.156 --> 00:27:28.640
under water.

00:27:28.640 --> 00:27:31.430
This was the day after
Christmas, 2006.

00:27:31.430 --> 00:27:32.300
Is that right?

00:27:32.300 --> 00:27:33.130
The big--

00:27:33.130 --> 00:27:34.170
2005?

00:27:34.170 --> 00:27:36.860
When was the big Boxing Day
tsunami on the Indian Ocean?

00:27:36.860 --> 00:27:37.920
AUDIENCE: 2004.

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:40.250
KEN JENNINGS: 2004.

00:27:40.250 --> 00:27:45.000
And this girl literally saved a
hundred lives by remembering

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.370
the right fact from her
geography teacher, at the

00:27:48.370 --> 00:27:48.960
right time.

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:51.700
You know, one fact, well
deployed, in the right place

00:27:51.700 --> 00:27:54.500
and at the right time,
was all it took.

00:27:54.500 --> 00:27:57.700
Most of the examples are not
going to be so dramatic.

00:27:57.700 --> 00:27:59.390
But I still believe that that's
true in general, that

00:27:59.390 --> 00:28:02.580
one fact, well deployed, in the
right place, does have the

00:28:02.580 --> 00:28:03.570
ability to change lives.

00:28:03.570 --> 00:28:08.505
And thank goodness, in our
generation we have tools that

00:28:08.505 --> 00:28:10.270
are just revolutionizing
the way we can

00:28:10.270 --> 00:28:12.610
retrieve these facts.

00:28:12.610 --> 00:28:16.130
But I also feel like we need
to have them on hand.

00:28:16.130 --> 00:28:19.670
We need to not outsource the
part of our brain that knows

00:28:19.670 --> 00:28:25.600
stuff, to our devices, no matter
how user friendly they

00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:31.150
are, how amazing their holiday
doodles, the level of snacks

00:28:31.150 --> 00:28:31.930
in their cafeteria.

00:28:31.930 --> 00:28:34.050
As much I love Google, I hope
that we still know things and

00:28:34.050 --> 00:28:38.630
it becomes a tool and not a
replacement for our memories.

