00:36:13.330 --> 00:36:13.970
He's a smart guy.

00:36:13.970 --> 00:36:17.280
When people ask him that, he
says back in the day I could

00:36:17.280 --> 00:36:18.330
have run the table.

00:36:18.330 --> 00:36:20.690
I could have held my own in
"Jeopardy." But it's a young

00:36:20.690 --> 00:36:21.420
man's game.

00:36:21.420 --> 00:36:22.935
And I'm past my prime now.

00:36:22.935 --> 00:36:27.150
So I think Alex feels he has
missed his chance at

00:36:27.150 --> 00:36:28.450
"Jeopardy" starting.

00:36:28.450 --> 00:36:30.560
Instead he gets to look like
a genius and be like

00:36:30.560 --> 00:36:32.260
oh no, no, I'm sorry.

00:36:32.260 --> 00:36:37.970
It's, what, is Tajikistan,
as if he knew?

00:36:37.970 --> 00:36:39.470
And he'll do the phony
pronunciations too.

00:36:39.470 --> 00:36:40.940
He'll be like, what
is Nicaragua?

00:36:44.200 --> 00:36:47.440
He loves doing the foreign
pronunciations.

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:48.690
I think he's a smart guy.

00:36:50.895 --> 00:36:51.370
Yeah?

00:36:51.370 --> 00:36:51.970
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:51.970 --> 00:36:52.780
I was curious.

00:36:52.780 --> 00:36:53.800
So I have an awful memory.

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:56.480
I was wondering if you've got
any memorization techniques

00:36:56.480 --> 00:36:59.170
that you use?

00:36:59.170 --> 00:37:02.230
KEN JENNINGS: People
ask me that a lot.

00:37:02.230 --> 00:37:04.490
And I feel bad, but I
don't have a trick.

00:37:04.490 --> 00:37:08.290
But I don't have a method or
an ancient Chinese herb or

00:37:08.290 --> 00:37:10.210
whatever it would take for me
to write a self-help book or

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:12.270
make a billion dollars
on this.

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:13.920
I read a book about
trivia nerds.

00:37:13.920 --> 00:37:16.500
And what I found out is that
most of these people

00:37:16.500 --> 00:37:18.110
apparently came out of
the box that way.

00:37:18.110 --> 00:37:20.880
There's something chromosomal
that makes some people

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:23.480
information sponges,
almost from birth.

00:37:23.480 --> 00:37:26.880
Nothing you can do about it.

00:37:26.880 --> 00:37:27.840
And I think it's relatable.

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:31.070
I mean we all are this way about
the things that we love.

00:37:31.070 --> 00:37:33.480
You take some kid that's
terrible in school, but he

00:37:33.480 --> 00:37:36.960
knows every word of every song
on his favorite album.

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:41.350
He knows every stat of his
favorite athlete or team, even

00:37:41.350 --> 00:37:42.810
if he doesn't know
his times tables.

00:37:42.810 --> 00:37:46.090
So it seems to me that interest
is the key thing that

00:37:46.090 --> 00:37:48.240
makes people either able to
remember stuff or not.

00:37:48.240 --> 00:37:50.660
If you care, you'll remember
it without even trying.

00:37:50.660 --> 00:37:54.870
If you don't, almost no amount
of effort will get

00:37:54.870 --> 00:37:58.050
it to stay in there.

00:37:58.050 --> 00:37:59.790
And these trivia people tend
to be interested in

00:37:59.790 --> 00:38:00.180
everything.

00:38:00.180 --> 00:38:03.810
They're just curious
people by nature.

00:38:03.810 --> 00:38:05.470
And I guess this sort of goes
to what I saying about the

00:38:05.470 --> 00:38:06.720
utility of information.

00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:13.710
Because they are curious about
everything, they'll find that

00:38:13.710 --> 00:38:16.030
their knowledge has
a social utility.

00:38:16.030 --> 00:38:17.750
They find it easier to
meet new people.

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:19.200
They'll sit next to somebody on
a plane and they'll be like

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:21.040
oh, you're from Fargo?

00:38:21.040 --> 00:38:22.820
Do you know that baseball
player, Roger

00:38:22.820 --> 00:38:23.670
Maris was from Fargo?

00:38:23.670 --> 00:38:25.850
Have you ever been to the
Roger Maris museum?

00:38:25.850 --> 00:38:30.140
The fact that they have this
wealth of seemingly useless

00:38:30.140 --> 00:38:34.700
facts actually, bizarrely makes
it very easy for them to

00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:37.170
get to know people.

00:38:37.170 --> 00:38:40.250
But getting back to your
question, I feel like when I

00:38:40.250 --> 00:38:42.420
was studying for "Jeopardy,"
there were things I tried to

00:38:42.420 --> 00:38:45.180
cram on and I just
did terribly.

00:38:45.180 --> 00:38:49.240
Like I had to memorize all the
presidents and their dates.

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:51.350
That's a "Jeopardy" stand by.

00:38:51.350 --> 00:38:52.420
I had know cocktails.

00:38:52.420 --> 00:38:53.770
I don't drink.

00:38:53.770 --> 00:38:56.560
But "Jeopardy" always has
the "potent potable."

00:38:56.560 --> 00:38:59.000
So I have all these
flashcards.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:00.030
I had two sets of flashcards.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:01.640
One have the presidents
on the front and the

00:39:01.640 --> 00:39:02.700
dates on the back.

00:39:02.700 --> 00:39:05.260
And the other had like on the
front it would be like, Harvey

00:39:05.260 --> 00:39:06.000
Wallbanger.

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:09.150
And the back it would be like,
whatever is in a Harvey Wall--

00:39:09.150 --> 00:39:11.430
I don't even know, vodka,
orange juice.

00:39:11.430 --> 00:39:13.320
It's like a screwdriver with
Galliano or something.

00:39:13.320 --> 00:39:14.250
Is that right?

00:39:14.250 --> 00:39:15.510
Who's like a functioning
alcoholic?

00:39:15.510 --> 00:39:16.760
Yeah, there you go.

00:39:19.920 --> 00:39:22.540
So for weeks, all we would talk
about in our house was

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:24.540
like the presidency and
cocktails, presidency.

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:26.070
It's like going to college with

00:39:26.070 --> 00:39:28.970
George W. Bush, I imagine.

00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:34.850
But thank you for laughing at my
very cheap political joke,

00:39:34.850 --> 00:39:38.350
cheap and out-of-date
political joke.

00:39:38.350 --> 00:39:39.630
But I found the same
thing you did.

00:39:39.630 --> 00:39:41.020
When these things were not
interesting to me, they were

00:39:41.020 --> 00:39:42.510
incredibly hard to remember.

00:39:42.510 --> 00:39:44.790
And I would make up a little
mnemonic stories, like I'm

00:39:44.790 --> 00:39:48.360
sure you do for hard
to remember facts.

00:39:48.360 --> 00:39:50.726
Like I had a hard time
remembering that John Quincy

00:39:50.726 --> 00:39:54.150
Adams was elected in
1824, for example.

00:39:54.150 --> 00:39:57.290
So I had to like make up this
very circuitous story in my

00:39:57.290 --> 00:40:03.290
head about Quincy, the 1970s,
late '70s, early '80s, TV

00:40:03.290 --> 00:40:06.110
medical examiner, working
a 24 hour shift.

00:40:06.110 --> 00:40:08.060
OK, Quincy working
a 24 hour shift.

00:40:08.060 --> 00:40:09.560
I can picture that.

00:40:09.560 --> 00:40:13.310
1984, or 1824, John Quincy
Adams, for some reason that

00:40:13.310 --> 00:40:13.830
would help me.

00:40:13.830 --> 00:40:16.300
And these things were always
more complicated than the fact

00:40:16.300 --> 00:40:18.410
I was trying to remember.

00:40:18.410 --> 00:40:20.940
But something about them was
more helpful to me than the

00:40:20.940 --> 00:40:24.070
fact itself.

00:40:24.070 --> 00:40:25.460
And there are techniques
that you can do.

00:40:25.460 --> 00:40:28.200
I mean have you heard about
this memory palace stuff?

00:40:28.200 --> 00:40:30.130
The part of our brain that does
geography is very good.

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:32.440
So if you need to remember
a bunch of facts in order

00:40:32.440 --> 00:40:34.790
quickly, you set up this mental
geography where you

00:40:34.790 --> 00:40:38.850
wander through your childhood
house and you place the memory

00:40:38.850 --> 00:40:41.480
sparking objects in a certain
order within the house.

00:40:41.480 --> 00:40:43.680
And there are people who can
use techniques like this to

00:40:43.680 --> 00:40:46.480
memorize all 52 cards in a deck
as fast as a dealer can

00:40:46.480 --> 00:40:47.720
turn them over.

00:40:47.720 --> 00:40:49.360
Like the guy will get done with
the deck and the person

00:40:49.360 --> 00:40:52.430
can then recite the deck by
re-walking through the place

00:40:52.430 --> 00:40:52.740
in his head.

00:40:52.740 --> 00:40:54.370
And these are people with
ordinary memories, but they've

00:40:54.370 --> 00:40:56.560
trained themselves to do
this parlor trick.

00:40:56.560 --> 00:40:57.650
So yes, there are
parlor tricks.

00:40:57.650 --> 00:41:00.880
And I'm terrible at them, I
guess is the short answer?

00:41:00.880 --> 00:41:01.800
Yes?

00:41:01.800 --> 00:41:03.020
AUDIENCE: Thanks are coming.

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:06.170
Like you, I grew up in a
pre-Google world of Birnbaum's

00:41:06.170 --> 00:41:07.250
books and--

00:41:07.250 --> 00:41:08.190
KEN JENNINGS: They're
old, huh?

00:41:08.190 --> 00:41:10.640
AUDIENCE: And Poundstone and
the "Book of Lists." And

00:41:10.640 --> 00:41:14.520
you've just published a book
of myths and trivia like

00:41:14.520 --> 00:41:16.410
these, in that tradition.

00:41:16.410 --> 00:41:20.340
Watson clearly demonstrates
that parsing and searching

00:41:20.340 --> 00:41:23.180
structured knowledge, that
someone has structured,

00:41:23.180 --> 00:41:23.790
[INAUDIBLE]

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:27.390
has structured for them, is
possible and can be made

00:41:27.390 --> 00:41:28.830
mechanical.

00:41:28.830 --> 00:41:32.150
There's still the thing that
Birnbaum does, that

00:41:32.150 --> 00:41:36.510
mythologists do, that people
who discover new facts and

00:41:36.510 --> 00:41:37.860
structure them.

00:41:37.860 --> 00:41:39.890
Given that you've just published
this book, could you

00:41:39.890 --> 00:41:41.600
speak a bit about that
and where that's

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:42.190
going in the future?

00:41:42.190 --> 00:41:46.210
Because there are more facts
being produced in

00:41:46.210 --> 00:41:47.350
more ways every day.

00:41:47.350 --> 00:41:49.680
We all know, we work
at Google.

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:53.280
What are your thoughts
on that?

00:41:53.280 --> 00:41:55.660
KEN JENNINGS: I mean this book
almost is sort of a throwback.

00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:59.290
I mean a lot of this stuff in
this book, it was published in

00:41:59.290 --> 00:42:02.300
academic journals.

00:42:02.300 --> 00:42:03.870
These questions are
less googleable

00:42:03.870 --> 00:42:05.660
than you'd think today.

00:42:05.660 --> 00:42:08.480
But many of them, all it would
take is a parent visiting

00:42:08.480 --> 00:42:11.920
Snopes or Wikipedia and they're
going to see the pros

00:42:11.920 --> 00:42:15.080
and cons of all these.

00:42:15.080 --> 00:42:16.310
But it's a good point.

00:42:16.310 --> 00:42:19.150
When they talk about Watson as
a diagnostician for example,

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:24.240
in Watson's new health care
adventures, yes it's going to

00:42:24.240 --> 00:42:26.110
be very good at recommending--

00:42:26.110 --> 00:42:29.230
you get a list of symptoms and
it'll recommend treatments and

00:42:29.230 --> 00:42:32.890
pharmaceutical possibilities
and suggest diagnoses.

00:42:32.890 --> 00:42:36.340
But it's not going to be
doing original work.

00:42:36.340 --> 00:42:37.913
It's not going to find
the new drug that

00:42:37.913 --> 00:42:39.040
will treat these things.

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:41.470
It'll just tell a doctor which
of these three options you

00:42:41.470 --> 00:42:43.510
already knew about, is
mathematically slightly more

00:42:43.510 --> 00:42:46.840
likely in this case.

00:42:46.840 --> 00:42:48.480
And that's the same thing
it was doing when it was

00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:50.460
answering "Jeopardy"
questions too.

00:42:50.460 --> 00:42:51.570
If you watched the show, you
could see the little

00:42:51.570 --> 00:42:53.780
probability meter at the
bottom of its screen.

00:42:53.780 --> 00:42:57.310
Sometimes it would make
incredibly naive errors.

00:42:57.310 --> 00:43:00.760
In the category of US cities, it
would say, what is Toronto?

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:03.140
Realizing that even though
some pattern-matching had

00:43:03.140 --> 00:43:05.890
worked, it had missed the most
important detail of all, that

00:43:05.890 --> 00:43:08.390
a human never would have missed,
which is that Toronto

00:43:08.390 --> 00:43:11.390
is not part of the US
until we invade it.

00:43:14.350 --> 00:43:17.400
But yeah, that distinction
still remains.

00:43:17.400 --> 00:43:20.230
I think a lot of lay people
would watch what Watson is

00:43:20.230 --> 00:43:21.720
doing and give it a little
too much credit.

00:43:21.720 --> 00:43:24.310
Wow, it understood
the question.

00:43:24.310 --> 00:43:26.170
And it didn't really
understood.

00:43:26.170 --> 00:43:31.150
It just could, in parallel,
weigh billions or trillions of

00:43:31.150 --> 00:43:34.800
textual relationships in a very
efficient and smart way.

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:36.650
Now, what's interesting is that
it could do that and get

00:43:36.650 --> 00:43:40.050
as good of results as a human,
doing what I would consider

00:43:40.050 --> 00:43:42.960
high-level work.

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:43.570
So, we'll see.

00:43:43.570 --> 00:43:46.620
But the creative part of those
jobs is still around.

00:43:46.620 --> 00:43:48.620
When Trebek got asked about
this, he'd always say I'm not

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:53.740
worried until Watson can host
"Jeopardy." I don't care if it

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:56.340
can win "Jeopardy," I just
wondering whether

00:43:56.340 --> 00:43:57.930
or not it can host?

00:43:57.930 --> 00:43:59.830
Do you have a question?

00:43:59.830 --> 00:44:01.730
AUDIENCE: I'm curious about your
relationship with your

00:44:01.730 --> 00:44:05.170
son with respect to facts
for instance.

00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:08.050
I think all of us probably
grow up pre-Wikipedia.

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:11.400
So my relationship with my
father was very much, he was

00:44:11.400 --> 00:44:15.970
the source of truth for many,
many years, until he stopped

00:44:15.970 --> 00:44:17.530
being the source
for any truth.

00:44:20.950 --> 00:44:22.660
And he did a pretty good job.

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:25.150
He's a very smart guy and
he's trivia focused.

00:44:25.150 --> 00:44:28.650
He kicked our ass in "Trivial
Pursuit" for years.

00:44:28.650 --> 00:44:30.010
And I grew up in--

00:44:30.010 --> 00:44:33.600
KEN JENNINGS: I think you dad is
trivia focused by the way.

00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:34.740
Like, that'll be on
his grave stone.

00:44:34.740 --> 00:44:37.480
AUDIENCE: His resume, yeah.

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:41.020
So once Wikipedia came up, I
sort of like fact-checked

00:44:41.020 --> 00:44:42.310
things when they came up.

00:44:42.310 --> 00:44:44.130
I'm like where do I know that?

00:44:44.130 --> 00:44:45.500
I think my dad just
made that up.

00:44:45.500 --> 00:44:46.750
And he was right.

00:44:46.750 --> 00:44:50.250
He was a pretty admirable job.

00:44:50.250 --> 00:44:53.200
But now you can do that
from the age of five.

00:44:53.200 --> 00:44:56.120
So you can't get away with just
pulling something out of

00:44:56.120 --> 00:44:59.630
your ass when your son asks,
as my dad did fairly

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:02.640
successfully for 16 years.

00:45:02.640 --> 00:45:04.690
So how has that changed
for you?

00:45:04.690 --> 00:45:06.150
You have a unique perspective.

00:45:06.150 --> 00:45:07.100
KEN JENNINGS: Are
you a parent?

00:45:07.100 --> 00:45:08.060
AUDIENCE: No, I'm not.

00:45:08.060 --> 00:45:10.000
KEN JENNINGS: Because when you
have kids you realize it's

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:10.820
another volume problem.

00:45:10.820 --> 00:45:14.220
You can't keep up with the
volume of why questions.

00:45:14.220 --> 00:45:16.580
And every time you answer a why
question with a "because,"

00:45:16.580 --> 00:45:18.390
there'll be another
well, why that?

00:45:18.390 --> 00:45:21.045
So you just get a higher level
thing and it becomes an

00:45:21.045 --> 00:45:22.295
endless recursive.

00:45:24.600 --> 00:45:26.780
I like to think that I'm pretty
good at saying I don't

00:45:26.780 --> 00:45:30.290
know, let's look it up, as
opposed to, I'll just make up

00:45:30.290 --> 00:45:32.710
for you how rainbows work.

00:45:32.710 --> 00:45:34.160
Why not?

00:45:34.160 --> 00:45:35.770
How are you going to
know any better?

00:45:35.770 --> 00:45:37.980
But the temptation is certainly
there, because it

00:45:37.980 --> 00:45:38.790
takes longer.

00:45:38.790 --> 00:45:42.960
It takes longer to look
it up and explain it.

00:45:42.960 --> 00:45:46.560
There's a "Calvin &amp; Hobbes"
cartoon where Calvin asks his

00:45:46.560 --> 00:45:48.910
dad why pictures are
black and white?

00:45:48.910 --> 00:45:51.540
And his dad says that's how
the world used to be then.

00:45:51.540 --> 00:45:54.690
Those are color photos of a
world that was black and white

00:45:54.690 --> 00:45:55.940
before you were born.

00:45:59.970 --> 00:46:01.170
And kids would we
believe that.

00:46:01.170 --> 00:46:03.110
But at some point,
they're going to

00:46:03.110 --> 00:46:04.110
realize that's not true.

00:46:04.110 --> 00:46:05.550
This is the first Christmas
where neither of my kids

00:46:05.550 --> 00:46:07.410
believes in Santa, so it's
very sad for us.

00:46:10.035 --> 00:46:11.640
But yeah, I do feel
like the right

00:46:11.640 --> 00:46:12.890
response is, I don't know.

00:46:12.890 --> 00:46:13.750
Let's look it up.

00:46:13.750 --> 00:46:16.140
Rather than ahh, stop
bugging me.

00:46:16.140 --> 00:46:17.890
Let me just tell you
something short.

00:46:17.890 --> 00:46:20.310
AUDIENCE: So he still
comes to you before

00:46:20.310 --> 00:46:21.570
seeking it out himself?

00:46:21.570 --> 00:46:22.200
KEN JENNINGS: He
actually does.

00:46:22.200 --> 00:46:25.360
And I like to think
that's laziness.

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:27.520
It's like the upside of the
lazy computer for our

00:46:27.520 --> 00:46:30.160
generation, is that as easy as
it is to do something online,

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:33.080
like asking the person there in
front of you is easier than

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:34.960
going to the computer and having
to type something in.

00:46:34.960 --> 00:46:36.750
That feels like homework.

00:46:36.750 --> 00:46:38.110
In fact, it is homework because
these kids are getting

00:46:38.110 --> 00:46:41.470
assigned to answer these
questions with Google.

00:46:41.470 --> 00:46:44.820
And so they don't see
this as fun anymore.

00:46:44.820 --> 00:46:47.890
So I guess that was very clever
of teachers to make it

00:46:47.890 --> 00:46:49.890
seem boring to actually have to
look stuff up, so that they

00:46:49.890 --> 00:46:50.760
still need their parents.

00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:52.310
That was good.

00:46:52.310 --> 00:46:53.480
Thank you.

00:46:53.480 --> 00:46:55.630
Do you have a question?

00:46:55.630 --> 00:46:55.840
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:46:55.840 --> 00:46:57.760
First of all I wanted to state
for the record, I also

00:46:57.760 --> 00:46:59.600
followed you when you were
historical in on "Jeopardy."

00:46:59.600 --> 00:47:01.590
And I was rooting for you.

00:47:01.590 --> 00:47:03.090
KEN JENNINGS: Well, that's
what we need.

00:47:03.090 --> 00:47:07.020
AUDIENCE: It was reassuring,
that $75K run-away at the end.

00:47:07.020 --> 00:47:08.230
So my question actually
was about the show.

00:47:08.230 --> 00:47:10.650
It seems like there are multiple
shows taped per day.

00:47:10.650 --> 00:47:12.750
So I was just curious a little
bit about that, logistics?

00:47:12.750 --> 00:47:14.580
And given your long run, how
many times did you have to go

00:47:14.580 --> 00:47:15.830
shopping in California?

00:47:18.390 --> 00:47:20.160
KEN JENNINGS: The logistics in
"Jeopardy" are interesting.

00:47:20.160 --> 00:47:21.300
What's the time on these.

00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:23.630
Is this the last question or,
do this and one more?

00:47:23.630 --> 00:47:25.900
OK.

00:47:25.900 --> 00:47:29.780
If you're a fan of the show, you
might get the wrong idea

00:47:29.780 --> 00:47:31.120
about how it works.

00:47:31.120 --> 00:47:33.330
Alex will come out every day and
pretend it's a new show.

00:47:33.330 --> 00:47:35.020
But really, they do
five in a day.

00:47:35.020 --> 00:47:37.270
So a full week's worth of
shows is an afternoon.

00:47:37.270 --> 00:47:38.240
And that's a long afternoon.

00:47:38.240 --> 00:47:42.050
Dick Clark I understand used to
do 10 shows of "Pyramid,"

00:47:42.050 --> 00:47:43.900
every day, which
blows my mind.

00:47:43.900 --> 00:47:47.930
Because I got so exhausted after
doing five "Jeopardys."

00:47:47.930 --> 00:47:50.150
So you show up in the morning,
get an orientation.

00:47:50.150 --> 00:47:53.120
They sort of walk you through
the tricky "Jeopardy" buzzer

00:47:53.120 --> 00:47:55.470
and what to do when you're on
stage, and don't freeze up,

00:47:55.470 --> 00:47:57.190
and let's rehearse
your anecdotes.

00:47:57.190 --> 00:47:59.450
Believe it or not, they do
rehearse those terrible

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:01.900
anecdotes they tell all
about their cats.

00:48:04.550 --> 00:48:08.790
And I guess I shouldn't say
they, we tell about our cats.

00:48:08.790 --> 00:48:12.260
But as soon as the game is over,
the contestants come

00:48:12.260 --> 00:48:12.770
down stage.

00:48:12.770 --> 00:48:15.140
There's this little awkward
chat down stage, which is

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:18.260
really a terrible
social dynamic.

00:48:18.260 --> 00:48:21.610
Because two of you have
just lost, seen your

00:48:21.610 --> 00:48:25.020
lifelong dream shattered.

00:48:25.020 --> 00:48:28.340
One of you has just realized he
or she is going to go back

00:48:28.340 --> 00:48:31.560
and do the whole thing again in
like 10 minutes, as soon as

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:33.460
you put on your tie or skirt.

00:48:33.460 --> 00:48:35.370
And the fourth one of you just
wants to get out of there in

00:48:35.370 --> 00:48:38.400
time because he's got
Laker tickets.

00:48:38.400 --> 00:48:41.480
Alex is always in a hurry.

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:43.800
And as soon as they say
we're clear, you

00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:44.745
get hustled off stage.

00:48:44.745 --> 00:48:47.100
The losers have to sign a piece
of paper accepting their

00:48:47.100 --> 00:48:48.400
consolation prizes.

00:48:48.400 --> 00:48:50.540
The winner and Alex get hustled
off to change their

00:48:50.540 --> 00:48:52.640
jacket, different dressing
rooms mind you.

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:55.760
And as soon as you got a new
tie, you come right back on,

00:48:55.760 --> 00:48:58.670
it's like, "on yesterday's
show."

00:48:58.670 --> 00:49:01.770
The real hitch for me was they
tape like three or four months

00:49:01.770 --> 00:49:03.980
in advance.

00:49:03.980 --> 00:49:06.160
So if you think about it, that's
not normally awkward.

00:49:06.160 --> 00:49:09.250
Somebody can be on the show,
they can either choose whether

00:49:09.250 --> 00:49:10.460
or not to tell their friends
how they did.

00:49:10.460 --> 00:49:12.280
And then a few months later,
they have a big viewing party

00:49:12.280 --> 00:49:16.210
and everybody cheers
or whatever.

00:49:16.210 --> 00:49:20.580
In my case, my show started
airing while I was still on.

00:49:20.580 --> 00:49:24.690
So I had 42 shows in the can
before one even aired--

00:49:24.690 --> 00:49:25.796
or 38?

00:49:25.796 --> 00:49:26.930
I think 38 shows in
the can before the

00:49:26.930 --> 00:49:28.130
first one even aired.

00:49:28.130 --> 00:49:33.430
So I was having to keep this
ever more momentous secret.

00:49:33.430 --> 00:49:35.600
I was having to fly back
secretly from Salt Lake, where

00:49:35.600 --> 00:49:39.290
we lived, down to LA,
twice a month.

00:49:39.290 --> 00:49:42.510
Stay there for 48 hours, win,
as it turned out, 10

00:49:42.510 --> 00:49:45.060
"Jeopardy" games at a head.

00:49:45.060 --> 00:49:45.640
Fly back.

00:49:45.640 --> 00:49:46.875
My boss was covering
for me at work.

00:49:46.875 --> 00:49:47.630
She was only one who knew.

00:49:47.630 --> 00:49:49.810
I hadn't told anybody else,
except my wife.

00:49:49.810 --> 00:49:51.070
My boss covered for
me at work.

00:49:51.070 --> 00:49:51.780
I'd fly back.

00:49:51.780 --> 00:49:54.480
And she'd tell everybody oh,
Ken's son was sick or Ken is

00:49:54.480 --> 00:49:57.020
painting his basement
or whatever.

00:49:57.020 --> 00:49:59.860
If you think like computer
programmers are smart, yeah,

00:49:59.860 --> 00:50:02.570
nobody ever figured it out.

00:50:02.570 --> 00:50:05.260
And I'd have to come back to
work the next day and like

00:50:05.260 --> 00:50:06.620
pretend I cared about
the morning

00:50:06.620 --> 00:50:07.870
staff meeting or whatever.

00:50:10.300 --> 00:50:13.330
You feel like you have
a secret identity.

00:50:13.330 --> 00:50:15.050
You're jetting off to do
something glamorous.

00:50:15.050 --> 00:50:17.050
I mean you got to come back to
the Daily Planet and be like,

00:50:17.050 --> 00:50:18.355
Lois, Superman was here?

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:24.900
I can't believe I
missed it again.

00:50:24.900 --> 00:50:27.810
It really did start to become
very confusing.

00:50:27.810 --> 00:50:29.560
You start to have the Spiderman
problem of all the

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:31.130
little lies you have to tell.

00:50:31.130 --> 00:50:33.890
If your parents call, you have
to pretend you're at home and

00:50:33.890 --> 00:50:37.800
not on the 405 driving to Culver
City to do a game show.

00:50:37.800 --> 00:50:39.950
And you don't have enough
changes of clothes,

00:50:39.950 --> 00:50:42.590
so what do you do?

00:50:42.590 --> 00:50:44.460
How do you get a sitter for the
kids, if my wife wanted to

00:50:44.460 --> 00:50:46.310
come out and watch a show?

00:50:46.310 --> 00:50:49.270
Do we do even have enough money
in the bank to cover

00:50:49.270 --> 00:50:50.850
like the hotel?

00:50:50.850 --> 00:50:52.910
Because "Jeopardy" does
not cover your travel

00:50:52.910 --> 00:50:53.125
arrangements.

00:50:53.125 --> 00:50:56.130
You fly out there on
your own dime.

00:50:56.130 --> 00:51:00.780
So yeah, it got logistically,
surprisingly complicated.

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:04.310
And it was a relief when I could
actually sort of tell

00:51:04.310 --> 00:51:06.690
what was going on.

00:51:06.690 --> 00:51:07.860
I didn't have enough clothes.

00:51:07.860 --> 00:51:08.580
I was a computer programmer.

00:51:08.580 --> 00:51:15.100
Like I don't have like 75
changes of business casual.

00:51:15.100 --> 00:51:17.200
Like if I wore the shorts
without the ketchup stain,

00:51:17.200 --> 00:51:20.020
that's like dressing up.

00:51:20.020 --> 00:51:22.280
So my brother is a lawyer
and he knew.

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:23.490
He and his wife had been
in the audience on

00:51:23.490 --> 00:51:24.160
the very first game.

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:25.100
So they knew what
was going on.

00:51:25.100 --> 00:51:27.300
So I would just borrow-- we're
about the same size.

00:51:27.300 --> 00:51:28.980
So he would lend me clothes.

00:51:28.980 --> 00:51:32.330
And really, you can rotate the
same cheap, JC Penney's

00:51:32.330 --> 00:51:34.070
clothes, over and over
on "Jeopardy,"

00:51:34.070 --> 00:51:35.040
and nobody ever notices.

00:51:35.040 --> 00:51:37.926
That's what I learned.

00:51:37.926 --> 00:51:39.870
I'd like to thank you all
for coming today.

00:51:39.870 --> 00:51:41.160
It was a real pleasure.

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:42.360
If you want a book, I'll
be happy to sign

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:43.500
them, up there I gather.

00:51:43.500 --> 00:51:44.750
But, thank you so much.

